The NIEUWLAND was bound for China. The ship called at Duins; arrival: 19-12-1794. On 10-01-1795 the NIEUWLAND cast anchor at Plymouth; there the English put an embargo on the ship and finally confiscated it.
In August 1795, the GEERTRUIDA was captured by the English at the Cape.
The OOSTHUIZEN was bound for China. Six days after it's departure from Texel the ship called at the Stilly Islands. In December 1795, the OOSTHUIZEN was confiscated by the English.
The WESTERMEER was bound for Batavia. Four days after the departure from Texel, however, the ship was seized by the French.
The WILLEMSTAD EN BOETSELAAR was bound  for Batavia. In August 1795, the ship was captured by the English at the Cape.
The ZORG called at Plymouth, 26-12-1794 till 04-11-1795. Three days after the departure from Plymouth the ship ran aground off Boulogne and was wrecked.
On 29-12-1794 the PRINS FREDERIK called at Duins. In December 1795, the ship was conficated by the English.

Return fleet (5001-5003) under command of oppercommies Kornelis de Houtman aboard the MAURITIUS. Total number of those on board 90. One of them died on the return voyage. April 26th. the HOLLANDIA lost the others out of sight, but May 26th. they met again at St. Helena.

Return fleet (5004-5007) under command of admiral Jakob van Neck aboard the MAURITIUS and vice-admiral Jan Jansz. Karel aboard the HOLLANDIA. From 26-04 till 04-05 at St. Helena. February 9th. Jakob Pietersz. became master.

Of the 4 ships (Molukse vloot) of the fleet of van Neck, which stayed behind under command of admiral van Warwijck and vice-admiral van Heemskerk, the GELDERLAND with the vice-admiral aboard and the ZEELANDIA left Bantam together. They reprovisioned from 08-12 till 01-01 at St. Helena,
Return fleet (5010-5011) under command of Gerard Le Roy aboard the LANGEBARK. When they arrived in Holland only 55 men were alive.
Return fleet (5012-5013) under command of admiral Guyon Le Fort. From 23-04 till 26-04 at St. Helena.

Of the 4 ships (Molukse vloot) of the fleet of van Neck, which stayed behind under command of admiral van Warwijck and vice-admiral van Heemskerk, the AMSTERDAM and the UTRECHT under command of van Warwijck were the last to leave the Indies. From 17-05 till 21-05 off St. Helena where they could not reprovision because of the Portuguese. From 30-05 till 31-05 at Ascension.
Return fleet (5018 and 5016) under command of vice-admiral Jakob Willekens, which left together with the fleet of Steven van der Haghen and the fleet of Pieter Both.
Return fleet (5020-5021) under command of Pieter Both; sailed together with the fleet of Steven van der Haghen and the fleet of Jakob Willekens.

Return fleet (5017, 5019, 5022) under command of admiral Steven van der Haghen aboard the ZON sailed together with the fleet of Pieter Both and the fleet of Jakob Willekens. From 06-07 till 12-07 at St. Helena.

Aboard the MAURITIUS was admiral Olivier van Noort, the first Dutchman who sailed around the world. On 01-05-1601 the ship passed the Cape of Good Hope; from 26 till 30-05-1601 it took on provisions at St. Helena.
Return fleet (5024-5025) under command of vice-admiral Paulus van Caerden. From 08-07 till 14-07 in the Mosselbaai; from 16-07 till 21-07 in the Vleesbaai; from 17-09 till 18-09 at St. Helena.

Return fleet (5029-5030) under command of admiral Kornelis Bastiaansz. From 06-03 till ± 20-03 at St. Helena where they took the Portuguese carrack SAN JAGO, which sailed to Zeeland under command of Laurens Bicker. From 08-04 till 13-05 at Fernado Noronha.
Sailed with the WITTE AREND and the ZWARTE AREND.

Return fleet (5034-5039) under command of Hans Schuurmans aboard the AMSTERDAM. From 22-06 till 08-09 at Mauritius; from 16-11 till 23-12 at St. Helena; from 09-01 till 22-01 at Fernando Noronha; from 27-03 till 14-04 at Falmouth.
Return fleet (5039-5041), under command of admiral W. Harmensz. and vice-admiral H. Brouwer which lost sight of the DUIFJE off Cape Agulhas. The DUIFJE sailed separately to Zeeland.
From 23-11 till 23-12 at St. Helena; from 09-01 till 22-01 at Fernando Lorentio.
From 25-11 till 23-12 at St. Helena; from 09-01 till 22-01 at Fernando Lorentio.
Return fleet (5042-5043) under command of admiral Jakob van Neck aboard the AMSTERDAM. From 03-03 till 24-03 at St. Helena.
Return fleet (5044-5045) under command of Gerard Le Roy. The fleet left St. Helena February 20th.
From 26-11 till 29-12 at St. Helena.
From 26-11 till 29-12 at St. Helena.
Ship of the Compagnie van De Moucheron, at the Cape 08-11-1603; from 26-11 till 29-12 at St. Helena.
Ship of the Compagnie van De Moucheron; at the Cape 08-11-1603; from 26-11 till 29-12 at St. Helena.
Ship of the Verenigde Compagnie; affected by shipworm and left behind in the Bay of Antongil; the cargo was taken over by the HOP VAN HOLLAND (5054).
Ship of the Verenigde Compagnie.
Returned to Holland with the cargo of the ALKMAAR (5050).
Ship of the Oude Oostindische Compagnie.
Somewhere off the Cape from 24-08 till 07-09; from 08-11 till 14-01 at St. Helena.
Reprovisioned somewhere near the Cape from 24-08 till 07-09; from 08-11 till 04-01 at St. Helena.
Reprovisioned somewhere near the Cape from 24-08 till 07-09; from 08-11 till 04-01 at St. Helena.
Ran ashore on the coast of Madagascar, 1606; the crew returned to Bantam.
Reprovisioned for one month at Mauritius.
Reprovisioned for one month at Mauritius.

The return fleet (5067-5071) under admiraal Wybrand van Warwijck. Because of leakage the HOLLANDIA and the DORDRECHT were forced to stay at Mauritius from 06-04 till 04-11-1606; 28-01 till 28-02-1607 at St. Helena. The remainder of the fleet stayed from 06-04 till 21-04 at Mauritius and left under command of Daniel van der Leek; from 30-06 till 08-07 at St. Helena.

Reinier Lambrechtsz. died shortly after sailing through the Sunda Strait; Olivier de Vivere, the vice-admiroal, died at Mauritius; departure from Mauritius October 13th.; from 19-12 till 06-01 at St. Helena.
Departure from Mauritius October 13th.; from 15-12 till 06-01 at St. Helena.
Until December 26th. at Mauritius (± 40 days) from 21-02 till 03-03 at St. Helena.
From 26-11 till 26-12 at Mauritius; from 21-02 till 03-03 at St. Helena; according to Mutter the date of arrival in Holland is 18-03-1608.
From 26-11 till 26-12 at Mauritius; from 21-02 till 03-03 at St. Helena.
From Bantam to Patani to take over the cargo of a Portuguese prize-ship, and lost on the coast of Guinea.
From 12-04 till 22-04 at Portland.
Because of leakage the ERASMUS was forced to stay at Mauritius.
Because of leakage the GROTE ZON was forced to return to Bantam; stayed in the Indies and was broken up.
Took over the cargo of the GROTE ZON.
Instructed to search for the ERASMUS (5081) at Mauritius; from 02-07 till 12-11 at Mauritius; left with 48 men of the ERASMUS.
Via Mauritius to search for the ERASMUS (5081).
In Saldanha Bay 14-03-1610; from 20-04 till 24-04 at St. Helena.
From 20-04 till 24-04 at St. Helena.
Via Mauritius and St. Helena; departure from St. Helena 19-03-1611.
Via Mauritius and St. Helena; departure from St. Helena 19-03-1611.
From 22-02 till 19-03 at St. Helena.
With crew and cargo of the ERASMUS (5081); departure from St. Helena 19-03-1611.
From 07-11 till 24-12 at Mauritius; from 05-01 till 12-01 at St. Lucia Bay; from 03-03 till 10-03 at St. Helena.
From 07-11 till 24-12 at Mauritius; from 05-01 till 12-01 at St. Lucia Bay; from 03-03 till 10-03 in St. Helena.
Ran ashore, sailing through the Amelander Gat and was lost.
Burnt in a fight with a Portuguese carrack off St. Helena, 13-06-1613; a part of the crew sailed back to Holland aboard the VLISSINGEN and the BANTAM (5098).
According to Valentijn departure on 30-12-1613.
According to Valentijn departure on 30-12-1613.
According to Valentijn departure on 17-10-1614.
Return fleet (5105-5108) with Pieter Both aboard the BANDA; this ship foundered on a reef in a hurricane near Mauritius; 30 deaths, including Pieter Both, 06-03-1615.
Via Mauritius; took over the cargo of the GELDERLAND (5107) and left Mauritius 12-04-1615.
Ran ashore in a hurricane near Mauritius and was lost, 06-03-1615.
Foundered on a reef near Mauritius during a hurricane, 06-03-1615; 30 deaths.
Took over the remaining cargo of the GELDERLAND (5107).
Took over the remaining cargo of the GELDERLAND (5107), BANDA (5105) and PROVINCIËN (5108) and the survivors of the GELDERLAND; from 08-02 till 08-03 at Mauritius.
Via St. Helena.
Via St. Helena.
From 26-12 till 03-01 at St. Helena.
From 26-12 till 03-01 at St. Helena.
From 24-01 till 30-01 at Mauritius; from 02-04 till 07-04 at St. Helena.
According to Valentijn also called NIEUW-ZEELAND; departure from St. Helena 07-04-1617.
According to Valentijn the ship sailed from Bantam 31-12-1617.
According to Valentijn this ship departed 31-12-1617.
According to Mac Lead the ship departed 19-01-1619. The DELFT left the fleet of J.P. Coen north of Java 14-01-1619 and sailed through Strait Bali to Holland via St. Helena.
February 24th from Saldanha Bay; from 16-03 till 25-03 at St. Helena.
Arrived at Plymouth 22-12-1620 where the English laid embargo on the ship, but it was soon released.
Via Masulipatnam, 03-10-1620.
According to Mac Lead the ship departed 27-05-1621.
According to Mac Lead the ship departed from the Coromandel, 25-11-1621.
Via St. Helena.
Via St. Helena; according to Valentijn the DORDRECHT sailed from Batavia, 06-11-1622.
From 12-06 till 20-06 at St. Helena.
Departure from St. Helena 20-06-1623.
From 12-06 till 20-06 at St. Helena.
From 12-06 till 20-06 at St. Helena.
At St. Helena, 08-06-1623. They sent a sloop with 10 men to the DELFSHAVEN (5157) to offer help, but due to a change of wind the LEEUW was forced to leave St. Helena, without its sloop and crew.
According to Mac Lead the ship departed 25-04-1623.
Via Persia.
Via Pulicat for gunpowder; departure 12-10-1624.
Lost in a storm near Madagascar, 18-03-1625.
Return fleet (5168-5170) under command of Kornelis Reiniersz.; the total number of those on board was 360. According to K.A. 994 the HOLLANDIA was in S. Lucia Bay from 27-03 till 25-04.
The master died before arrival at the Cape; via Mascarenes, arrival 01-04-1625 and from 10-04 till 25-10 in the Bay of Antongil; fougth 2 Portuguese carracks near St. Helena, afterwards lost.
Stayed for 3 months at Mauritius; according to Dunlop f451,043.
Stayed for 3 months at Mauritius; forced by a heavy storm to sail to Plymouth, January 1626.
Departure from Pulicat 31-05-1625; via Mauritius, and Plymouth, because of leakage and a broken rudder after a storm, January 1626.
From 24-02 till 11-03 at St. Helena; 16-06 at Plymouth. According to Daghregister the EENDRACHT left Batavia 28-10-1625.
From 24-02 till 11-03 at St. Helena; 16-06 at Plymouth. According to Daghregister the HOORN left Batavia 28-10-1625.

Return fleet (5177-5180) under command of Pieter Kornelisz.; the total number of those on board was 400; the AMSTERDAM, the DELFT and the WAPEN VAN ROTTERDAM were ships of the Nassause vloot; according to the Daghregister: the departure was 05-02-1626. The AMSTERDAM was, according to the Daghregister, also called the WAPEN VAN AMSTERDAM.
According to the Daghregister the DELFT was also called WAPEN VAN DELFT.
Sailed separately.
From 25-06 till 10-11-1626 in the Bay of Antongil and wandered for about 5 months between Madagascar and the Cape.
Chained up for 12 months and 10 days at the Isle of Wight.
Ship of the Nassause vloot; chained up for about one year at the Isle of Wight.
Chained up for 12 months and 10 days at the Isle of Wight.
Via St. Helena.
Via St. Helena.
Via St. Helena.
Via St. Helena; ship of the Nassause vloot.
Via St. Helena; in Valentijn mentioned as the GROOT HOLLANDIA.
According to Mac Lead the DORDRECHT departed 16-12-1627; according to K.A. 1007 the cargo was f339,674.

Because of bad trimming (rankheid) of the ship, the VIANEN returned to Batavia and sailed again 14-01 1628 via Strait Bali; via the west coast of Australia where it struck on a reef (21°S) without serious damage.
From 24-12 till 16-01 at Mauritius; from 19-03 till 14-04 at St. Helena.
From 24-12 till 16-01 at Mauritius; from 06-04 till 14-04 at St. Helena.
From 24-12 till 16-01 at Mauritius; from 19-03 till 14-04 at St. Helena.
From 26-12 till 30-01 at Mauritius; from 06-04 till 14-04 at St. Helena.
From 26-12 till 30-01 at Mauritius; from 06-04 till 14-04 at St. Helena.
From 26-12 till 30-01 at Mauritius; from 06-04 till 14-04 at St. Helena.
Burnt on 20-04 or 30-04 at 4°33' North.

Return fleet (5202-5210) under command of Pieter van den Broeke, which, according to Valentijn, departed 15-12-1629 from Batavia; from 17-03 till 23-03 at St. Helena. The GALIASSE strayed off the fleet and sailed via the Irish Sea to Holland.
Return fleet (5211-5217) under command of Anthonie van Diemen aboard the DEVENTER 13-07-1631 off St. Helena.
Lost off Texel.
Return fleet (5218-5222) under command of Dirk van der Lee aboard the NASSAU.
Lost near the Borkumer Rif, August 1632.
Together with the TER VEERE; from Mauritius 19-05-1632 via S. Augustin where they stayed from 15-07 till 17-09. They had to wait for the return fleet at St. Helena.
Return fleet (5225-5229) under command of Jakob Speckx aboard the PRINS WILLEM. Via St. Helena, from 15-04 till 26-04.
Joined the return fleet of Speckx at the Cape.
Joined the return fleet of Speckx at St. Helena.
Together with the LEEUWARDEN; from 17-12 till 29-12 at Gamron; via St. Helena.
Return fleet (5234-5235) under command of Willem Jansz. van Amersfoort aboard the WEZEL; sailed via St. Helena.
Via St. Helena.
Together with the AMSTERDAM from Surat under command of Lukasz.; sailed via St. Helena.
Departure from Surat with a crew of 100 men 27-11-1634; joined at the Cape the return fleet of Pieter Vlak.
Joined at the Cape the return fleet of Pieter Vlak.
Return fleet (5240-5242) under command of Willem Jakobsz. Koster aboard the PRINS WILLEM joined at the Cape the return fleet of Pieter Vlak.
Return fleet (5243-5244) under command of Pieter Vlak aboard the BANDA; joined the fleet of Koster at the Cape. Vlak became commandeur of both fleets; from 13-04 till 20-04 at St. Helena.
Return fleet (5245-5250), under command of Hendrik Brouwer; at the Cape joining the FREDERIK HENDRIK (5251 ) and at St. Helena probably the AMBOINA (5252); at St. Helena from 16-04 till 30-04.
Sailed separately from Surat and joined the return fleet probably off St. Helena; master died 27-08 at Shetland Isl.
Return fleet (5253-5257) under command of Hans Puntmans aboard the BANDA; from 21-04 till 15-05 at St. Helena.
According to the Daghregister the cargo was f 268,960.
Ran ashore in the Sunda Strait, off Varkenseiland, 02-01-1637. Part of the cargo was lost, crew saved and ship broken up.
Also called NIEUW-ZEELAND.
Sailed together with the return fleet of Puntmans.
Sailed together with the ZWOLLE.
Sailed together with the AEMILIA.
Return fleet (5261-5266) under command of Artus Gijsels aboard the WEZEL; from 01-04 till 25-04 at St. Helena.
Joined the return fleet of Gijsels at St. Helena on 16-04.
Joined the return fleet of Gijsels at St. Helena and stayed there from 06-04 till 25-04.
Return fleet (5268-5272) under command of Jochem Roelofsz. van Deutekom aboard the ZUTPHEN. The fleet sailed via St. Helena.
Return fleet (5273-5274) under command of Karel Reiniers aboard the ZWOLLE, sailed via St. Helena.
Wrecked off Texel.

Return fleet (5276-5279) undercommand of Koekebakker aboard the AMSTERDAM; from 12-04 till 25-04 at St. Helena, where they joined the return fleet of Schouten. The fleet was under command of Koekebakker.
Return fleet (5280-5282) under command of Kornelis Schouten aboard the MARIA DE MEDICI joined the return fleet of Koekebakker at St. Helena; Schouten became vice-commandeur.
From 05-04 till 25-04 at St. Helena. At the Cape 33 survivors of the KONING DAVID (0524) were taken on board of the fleet.
Joined the return fleet of Koekebakker at the Cape.
Sailed together with the PETTEN.
Return fleet (5286-5291) under command of Barend Pietersz. Grotebroek, who died during the voyage and was succeeded by Jakob Martensen (05-02). The BANDA had 11 Portuguese prisoners on board.
With 17 Portuguese prisoners on board.
With 13 Portuguese prisoners on board.
With 14 Portuguese prisoners on board.
With 11 Portuguese prisoners on board.
With 12 Portuguese prisoners on board.
Return fleet (5292-5294) under command of Kornelis Jansz. Silvius aboard the HAARLEM. The BERKHOUT was also called BERKEL. Because of a gale from 23-03 till 08-05 at Mauritius; via St. Helena.
The master Adriaan Tonneman died 09-06 and was succeeded by Andries Adriaansz. Because of a gale from 22-03 till 28-10 at Mauritius; from 24-01-1642 till 23-03 at St. Helena.
Sailed alone.
Return fleet (5296-5300) under command of Francois Caron aboard the VOGELSTRUIS. From 11-04 till 24-04 at St. Helena.
Joined, together with the WALVIS, the return fleet of Caron at the Cape.
Joined, together with the SNOEK, the return fleet of Caron at the Cape.
Joined, together with the WEZEL, the return fleet of Caron at St. Helena; from 17-04 till 24-04 at St. Helena.
Joined, together with the AMSTERDAM the return fleet of Caron at St. Helena; from 18-04 till 24-04 at St. Helena.
Return fleet (5305-5313, except 5307, with 1050 men on board at departure) under command of Karel Hartsing aboard the VREDE. From 30-03 till 12-04 at St. Helena.
Joined the return fleet of Hartsing at St. Helena. Broken up in 1643.
Joined the return fleet of Hartsing at St. Helena where the ship arrived April 5th.
Return fleet (5315-5319 with 711 men onboard at departure) under command of Anthonie Caan aboard the WALVIS and Jan Dirksz. Gale aboard the HOP VAN ZEELAND. Via St. Helena.
Sailed alone.
Sailed alone.
Fleet (5322-5326) under command of Paulus Krook aboard the WITTE OLIFANT. Via St. Helena, from where they left 26-04. Total number of those on board 658.
Together with HAARLEM under command of Jan van Elserak; met the fleet of Krook at St. Helena. Elserak became vice-commandeur aboard the ZEELANDIA. The fleet left 26-04.
'Adviesschip' sailed via La Rochelle, where it waited for a convoy to Holland.
Fleet (5330-5337) under command of Maximiliaan le Maire aboard the TIJGER. Total number of those on board (HENRIETTE LOUISE not included) 1062.
According to Coolhaas the invoice value of the return cargo was 338,219.
Return fleet (5339-5345) under command of Jeremias van Vliet aboard the VOGELSTRUIS. Total number of those on board 939.

Second return fleet (5346-5348) under command of vice-commandeur Reinier van 't Zuim aboard the WITTE OLIFANT. The HAARLEM was wrecked 25-03-1647 in Table Bay, between Robben Island and the mainland. The fleet sailed via St. Helena.
Return fleet (5349-5360 with 1600 men on board at departure) under command of Wollebrant Geleijnsen de Jong sailed via St. Helena.
Return fleet (5361-5369) under command of Pieter Sijmen aboard the MALAKKA. Total number of those on board 1124. Via St. Helena.
Return fleet (5370-5378) under command of Arend Barendsz. aboard the DIAMANT.
Return fleet (5379-5385) under command of Arnoud Heussen aboard the WALVIS.
Second return fleet (5386, 5387, 5391) under command of Van der Lijn.
Return fleet (5389-5395 except 5391) under command of Joan van Teylingen aboard the DIAMANT. Total number of those on board 762, amongst whom 28 passengers.
141 men including 11 passengers.
109 men including 2 passengers.
Return fleet (5396-5400) under command of Dirk Ogel aboard the SALAMANDER(?).

Return fleet (5401-5405) under command of Gerard Demmer aboard the PAREL; after the Cape Andries Frisius became commandeur. Total number of those on board 765. The MALAKKA was unloaded at Bergen, October 1653.
Second return fleet (5406-5408) under command of Andries Frisius, who became commandeur of the joined fleets.
Captured from the English.
Return fleet (5409-5414) under command of Pieter Kemp. At St. Helena they waited for the ROTTERDAM and the PRINS WILLEM. Arrival at St. Helena 18-04-1654.

Return fleet (541 7-5420) under command of Huibert de Laresse. Vice-commandeur was Hubert Hugo aboard the TERSCHELLING. Total number of those aboard 327 including 14 women and children. Via St. Helena, departure 06-03-1655.
Return fleet (5421-5429) under command of Rijklof van Goens aboard the PAREL(?). Total number of those aboard 839.
Via St. Helena.
Via St. Helena.
Via St. Helena.
Via St. Helena.
Via St. Helena.
Via St. Helena.
Via St. Helena.
First return fleet (5431-5436) under command of Kasper van den Bogaard aboard the VERENIGDE PROVINCIEN(?). Via St. Helena? Total number of those aboard 832.
Second return fleet (5437-5440) under command of Dirk Sarcerius. Arrival at St. Helena 17-05-1656 and stayed there for at least 10 days.
First return fleet (5441-5446) under command of Thijs Krab aboard the PRINS WILLEM. Total number of those on board 528 seamen, 235 soldiers and 108 passengers (Portuguese).

Second return fleet (5447-5450) under command of Volker Westerwold. Via Mauritius (arrival 02-07-1657) and Madagascar because of damage. Overtaken at St. Helena by the return fleet of 18-12-1657. Before the ARNHEM had left the Sunda Strait, two masters had died: Jan Rotgans and Pieter Jansz. de Vries; the third one, Van Bergen, was dismissed at the Cape for being unable to maintain order. His successor was Jan Simonsz. Klos.
The AVONDSTER returned to Batavia because of leakage (28-02-1657). Part of the cargo was taken over by the PAREL. It stayed in the Indies and was wrecked in the Bay of Gale (Ceylon) (02-07-1659).
Departure from Cape with 157 men.
Via Mauritius (arrival 27-06 or 02-07) in order to wait for the return fleet of 18-12-1657.

First return fleet (5451-5456) under command of Johan Kunaeus aboard the PAREL. Via St. Helena. The ACHILLES was sent ahead to St. Helena with instructions for the ARNHEM and the SLOT VAN HONINGEN to wait for the fleet.
See also 5448.
Second return fleet (5457-5460) under command of Kornelis Kwaalberge. The ENKHUIZEN arrived at the Cape with 150 men.
The PRINSES ROYAAL arrived at the Cape with 160 men.
First return fleet (5461-5468) under command of Izaak Koedijk, with 160 Portuguese prisoners on board. The AMERSFOORT called at St. Helena (10-03 till 08-04).
From 25/28-03 till 08-04-1659 at St. Helena.
From 25/28-03 till 08-04-1659 at St. Helena.
From 9/10-03 till 08-04-1659 at St. Helena.
From 25/28-03 till 08-04-1659 at St. Helena.
From 25/28-03 till 08-04-1659 at St. Helena.
From 9/10-03 till 08-04-1659 at St. Helena.
From 9/10-03 till 08-04-1659 at St. Helena.

The master died and was succeeded by Pieter Gerritsz. Second return fleet (5469-5470) under command of Van Twist aboard the NAARDEN. Both ships lost each other out of sight, 29/30-03-1659. The ERASMUS sailed via the Comoro Islands and Madagascar because of damage. At the Cape it waited for the return fleet of 18-12-1659. The ship called at St. Helena. The crew included 16 Portuguese prisoners.
The crew included 16 Portuguese prisoners; 14 of them were taken over by the DOLPHIN, an English ship.
First return fleet (5471-5479) under command of Pieter Sterthenius aboard the WAPEN VAN HOLLAND. At the Cape the ERASMUS joined the fleet.
The crew included 3 passengers.
The crew included 2 passengers.
Second return fleet (5480-5481).

First return fleet (5482-5488) with, except the already mentioned members, 60 passengers at departure under command of Andries Frisius aboard the WAPEN VAN AMSTERDAM. The total number of deaths before the Cape was 43. Ten stowaways were put aboard the ANKEVEEN at the Cape (see 0930). Via St. Helena.
Second return fleet (5489-5490) under command of Johan Bouchellon. The crew included 7 passengers.

First return fleet (5491-5497) under command of Arnold de Vlaming van Oudshoorn(t) aboard the WAPEN VAN HOLLAND and Jakob Willemsz. (vice-comm. @+@ ). At the Cape the fleet waited for the return fleet of 30-01-1662. Johan van der Laan became the new commander. The ARNHEM was wrecked at Brandao, an island east of Madagascar (12-02-1662); about 80 survivors reached Mauritius and were picked up later.
Was wrecked in the Indian Ocean during a storm at 25/26° S. (10-02-1662).
Was wrecked in the Indian Ocean during a storm at 25/26° S (10/11-02-1662).
The crew included 15 passengers.
Was wrecked in the Indian Ocean during a storm at 25/26° S. (10/11-02-1662).
Second return fleet (5498-5499) under command of Zacharias Wagenaar. After the Cape under command of Johan van der Laan (see above). The ANJELIER was wrecked at Terschelling(?).
The crew included 5 passengers.
The SPREEUW sailed on its own with message of the loss of Taiwan.

First return fleet (5501-5508) under command of Herman Klenke van Odessen aboard the WAPEN VAN AMSTERDAM. At the Cape the MEIBOOM joined the fleet. Unsuccessful voyage of discovery to the non-existent island New Helena.
Joined the fleet of 26-12-1662 at the Cape. This adviesjacht brought the message of the Dutch conquest of Cochin.
Second return fleet (5510-5511) under command of Kornelis Vonk.

First return fleet (5512-5520) under command of Dirk Steur aboard the ORANJE (551 7) and Adriaan van der Meide aboard the MAARSEVEEN (5515), with 760 seafarers, 207 soldiers, 31 passengers, and 113 Portuguese prisoners. Before the Cape 79 men died. At the Cape the BEURS VAN AMSTERDAM (5521) and the LOOSDUINEN (5522) joined the fleet.
Aboard the MAARSSEVEEN was Adriaan van der Meide, vice-commandeur of the return fleet. The ship was wrecked in the battle of Lowestoft against the English, 13-06-1665.
The NAGELBOOM was hired by the Admiralties to fight the English; it was taken by the English on 13-06-1665.
Aboard the ORANJE was Dirk Steur, commandeur of the return fleet. The ship was hired by the Admiralties to fight the English; it was burnt in the battle of Lowestoft, 13-06-1665.
Four stowaways discovered.
Was hired by the Admiralties to fight the English; taken by the English on 19-09-1665.
Second return fleet (5521-5522); joined the return fleet of 21-12-1663 at the Cape.

First return fleet (5523-5533) under command of Pieter de Bitter aboard the WALCHEREN (5532) and Jakob Burkhorst aboard the PHOENIX (5530). At the Cape the KOGGE and the NIEUWENHOVE (5534 and 5535) joined the fleet. The combined fleet sailed via Bergen (Norway) because of the war; 12-08-1665: battle in the Bay of Bergen against an English fleet (25 men killed and 70 wounded). After the departure from Bergen two ships were taken by the English (see below). The AMSTELLAND returned to Bergen on 16-09-1665; departure: in October. On 25-10-1665 the ship was wrecked east of Terschelling; its cargo was mainly saved.
Via Bergen (08-08 till 02-09-1665).
Via Bergen, departure on 02-09-1665.
Via Bergen (08-08 till 02-09-1665). Taken on 13-09-1665 by the English at Dogger Bank.
Via Bergen (08-08 till 02-09-1665) and Gluckstadt on the Elbe.
Was wrecked in a storm near the Cape (Febr. 1665).
Via Trondheim, not via Bergen.
Aboard the PHOENIX was Jakob Burkhorst, vice-commandeur of the return fleet. The ship sailed via Bergen (call: 08-08 till 02-09-1665); on 13-09-1665 it was taken by the English at Dogger Bank.
Via Bergen, departure on 02-09-1665; returned to Norway (Flecker Ö and Kristiansand).
Aboard the WALCHEREN was Pieter de Bitter, commandeur of the return fleet. The ship sailed via Bergen (08-08 till 02-09-1665).
Via Bergen (08-08 till 02-09-1665) and Denmark (Kronborg). Returned  under  convoy  in  the  fleet  of schout-bij-nacht Stachouwer of the Admiralty of Friesland.

Second return fleet (5534-5535), joined the first return fleet (see 5523) at the Cape. According to Daghregister 1665 the KOGGE carried a cargo of 88,576. The ship called at Bergen; departure: 02-09-1665. Later on it returned to Norway (Flecker Ö and Kristiansand).
Via Trondheim (not via Bergen) and Flecker Ö. The crew included 2 passengers.

Separate fleet (5536-5537) from Bengal via Ceylon (departure on 29-12-1665) and Malabar; joined the fleet of 30-01-1666 at the Cape. The original cargo of the KALF from Bengal had an invoice value of 190,754. The ship sailed via Bergen. It was wrecked in the Vlie, 22 men were saved.
Original cargo from Bengal: 364,044. The VENENBURG was taken by the English.
Return fleet (5538-5542) under command of Jakob Kauw aboard the WASSENDE MAAN (5540), with 356 men and 11 passengers. At the Cape the KALF and the VENENBURG (5536 and 5537) joined the fleet.
Aboard the WASSENDE MAAN was Jakob Kauw, commandeur of the return fleet.

Immediately after the departure from Batavia the VOGELZANG made water, the ship was repaired at Panjon. It sailed via Saldanha Bay (arrival: 25-04-1666). At the Cape the problem of leakage occurred again.
Separate fleet (5543-5545) from Bengal via Ceylon (19-01-1667) and Malabar, joined the return fleet of 26-01-1667 at the Cape. Original cargo of the CECILIA from Batavia: 17,415.
Original cargo from Batavia: 17,730.
Original cargo from Batavia: 18,317.

Return fleet (5546-5554) under command of Johan van Dam aboard the ZUIDPOLSBROEK (5554). At the Cape the CECILIA, the OPPERDOES, and the SPARENDAM (5543-5545) joined the fleet. The crew of the AMERSFOORT included one passenger.
On 19-09-1667 the WAPEN VAN AMSTERDAM was wrecked south of Iceland; 14 men were saved.
Was wrecked near the Faeroe Is. in September 1667. Many men were drowned.
The crew included 2 passengers. Aboard the ZUIDPOLSBROEK was Johan van Dam, commandeur of the return fleet.
First return fleet (5555-5557) under command of Jan van de Werf, master of the WAPEN VAN HOORN (5556).
Jan van de Werve was commandeur of the return fleet. According to K.A. 1156 the cargo was destined for the chamber of Hoorn.

Second return fleet (5558-5563) under command of Van der Laan aboard the HOLLANDSE TUIN (5562) and Wagenaar aboard the WAPEN VAN MIDDELBURG (5560). At the Cape the AMERONGEN, the JONGE PRINS, the VRIJHEID, and the SPREEUW (5564-5567) joined the fleet.
Aboard the WAPEN VAN MIDDELBURG was Wagenaar, vice-commandeur of the return fleet.
Aboard the HOLLANDSE TUIN was Van der Laan, commandeur of the return fleet.
Aboard the HOLLANDSE TUIN was Van der Laan, commandeur of the return fleet.
Third return fleet (5564-5566). Joined the fleet of 07-12-1667 at the Cape. The crew of the AMERONGEN included 3 passengers.
According to Daghregister 1667 the SPREEUW carried a cargo of 170,212. The ship joined the fleet of 07-12 and that of 24-12-1667 at the Cape.

First return fleet (5571-5578) under command of Johan Thijssen aboard the ZUIDPOLSBROEK (5578). Seven heavy storms harassed the fleet before it reached the Cape. The fleet of 14-12 and that of 20-12-1668 joined the command of Johan Thijssen. According to Daghregister 1668/9 the BATAVIA arrived at the Cape on 01-03-1669. The crew included one passenger.
The crew included 7 passengers.
The crew included 10 passengers.
The crew included 4 passengers.
The crew included 10 passengers.
The crew included 5 passengers.

The crew included 4 passengers; 10 extra seafarers were taken over from the WILGENBURG. According to Daghregister 1668/9 the ship arrived at the Cape on 01-03-1669. Aboard the ZUIDPOLSBROEK was Johan Thijssen, commandeur of the return fleet.
Second return fleet (5579-5580) under command of Enoch Poolvoet aboard the OOSTENBURG; joined the fleet of 01-12-1668 at the Cape.
The crew included one passenger. Aboard the OOSTENBURG was Enoch Poolvoet, commandeur of the return fleet.
Third return fleet (5581-5583). Joined the fleet of 01-12-1668 at the Cape.
The crew included 10 passengers.
According to Daghregister 1668/9: cargo 160,990.
Fleet from Ceylon (5584-5587) under command of Rijklof van Goens (Junior) aboard the KOGGE.
Aboard the KOGGE was Rijklof van Goens (Junior), commandeur of the return fleet.
Fourth return fleet (5588-5589).
According to Coolhaas III: cargo 237,020.
First return fleet (5590-5599) under command of Mattheus van den Broek aboard the HOLLANDSE TUIN (5598), with 1145 men and 29 passengers. At the Cape the fleet of 17-12-1668 joined this fleet.
The crew included 6 passengers.
According to Daghregister 1668/9: cargo 285,732.
The crew included 4 passengers. Aboard the HOLLANDSE TUIN was Mattheus van den Broek, commandeur of the return fleet.
Second return fleet (5600-5604) under command of Johannes Massis aboard the DAMIATE. Joined the fleet of 18-11-1669 at the Cape. The crew of the DAMIATE included 5 passengers.
The crew included 5 passengers.
The fleet (5605-5606) from Ceylon joined the fleet of 01-02-1670 at the Cape.
Third return fleet (5607-5608). The fleet from Ceylon joined this fleet at the Cape.

First return fleet (5609-5616) under command of IJsbrand Goske aboard the STICHT VAN UTRECHT (5614). At the Cape the HUIS TE VELSEN (5617) and the fleet of 19-12-1670 from Ceylon joined this fleet. According to Daghregister 1671 the fleet left the Cape on 16-03-1671.
Aboard the STICHT VAN UTRECHT was IJsbrand Goske, commandeur of the return fleet.
Joined the fleet of 19-11-1670 at the Cape.

Second return fleet (5618-5621) under command of Pieter Koopman aboard the VRIJHEID (5620). At the Cape the SPANBROEK (5624) joined the fleet. According to K.A. 3984 the fleet left the Cape on 20-03-1671.
The crew included 2 passengers. Aboard the VRIJHEID was Pieter Koopman, commandeur of the return fleet.
The crew included 6 passengers.
The fleet (5622-5623) from Ceylon joined the fleet of 19-11-1670 at the Cape. According to K.A.3984 the fleet left Ceylon on 25-12-1670.
Joined the fleet of 16-12-1670 at the Cape.
Third return fleet (5625-5626).
After a dinner at the Cape the master was stabbed in a quarrel and died. His successor was Isaak Fontein.

First return fleet (5627-5636) under command of commandeur Arnoud van Overbeke aboard the TIDORE (5633), vice-commandeur Schimmelpennink aboard the TERNATE (5632), and schout-bij-nacht Sanderus aboard the DELFSHAVEN. At the Cape the fleet of 20-01-1672 from Ceylon and the fleet of 04-02-1672 joined this fleet. According to K.A. 3984 the combined fleet left the Cape on 19-04-1672.
Via St. Helena.
Aboard the TERNATE was Schimmelpennink, vice-commandeur of the return fleet.
Aboard the TIDORE was Arnoud van Overbeke, commandeur of the return fleet.
The fleet (5637-5639) from Ceylon under command of Johan de Barra joined the fleet of 20-12-1671 at the Cape. According to K.A. 3984 the combined fleet left the Cape on 19-04-1672.
Second return fleet (5640-5641); joined the fleet of 20-12-1671 at the Cape. According to K.A. 3984 the combined fleet left the Cape on 19-04-1672.

Return fleet (5642-5647) under command of Abraham Huibrechtsen aboard the WAPEN VAN VEERE (5647) and Eduard Goudsmit aboard the PIJNACKER (5645). The ALPHEN was taken by the English at St. Helena, May 1673.

The EUROPA originally was a French ship, captured in the Indies (October 1672). According to Daghregister 1673/4 the ship left the Cape on 10-05-1673. At St. Helena it was taken by the English, May 1673.
Due to wrong instructions the PAPENBURG was taken by the English off Texel, August 1673.
Aboard the PIJNACKER was Eduard Goudsmit, vice-commandeur of the return fleet.
Aboard the WAPEN VAN VEERE was Abraham Huibrechtsen, commandeur of the return fleet. The ship was taken by the English at St. Helena, May 1673.
Sailed via Bergen (Norway).

Return fleet (5650-5658) under command of Nikolaas de Rooi aboard the BURCHT VAN LEIDEN (5654), Jan Blauwmeulen aboard the MIDDELBURG (5655), and Jan Lambertsz. Radder aboard the BUREN (5653). At the Cape the ZWEMMER (5659) joined the fleet. The BAARS carried rice to the Cape and sailed on to patria.
Acc. to Daghregister 1674 the ship arrived at the Cape on 02 or 04-05-1674.
Aboard the BUREN was Jan Lambertsz. Radder, schout-bij-nacht of the return fleet.
Aboard the BURCHT VAN LEIDEN was Nikolaas de Rooi, commandeur of the return fleet.

The MIDDELBURG sailed via Anjouan (09-06-1674) and the Mayotte Islands (12-08 till 03-10-1674), meeting with many difficulties and loosing about 60 men. The ship joined the fleet of 18-11-1674 at the Cape. Aboard the MIDDELBURG was Jan Blauwmeulen, vice-commandeur of the return fleet.
Joined the fleet of 04-02-1674 at the Cape.

First return fleet (5660-5666) under command of Kornelis Valkenier aboard the MAKASSAR (5661), Adam van Breen aboard the TIDORE (5663), and Jakob Ganswijk aboard the VRIJE ZEE (5666). At the Cape the MIDDELBURG (5655) and the KROONVOGEL (5674) joined the fleet.
Aboard the MAKASSAR was Kornelis Valkenier, commandeur of the return fleet.
According to Valentijn: cargo 337,695. Aboard the TIDORE was Adam van Breen, vice-commandeur of the return fleet.

Immediately after passing through Sunda Strait the ship lost sight of the fleet. Due to a French attack it did not call at the Cape, and sailed via Pernambuco (Brazil). Aboard the VRIJE ZEE was Jakob Ganswijk, schout-bij-nacht of the return fleet.
The fleet from Ceylon (5668-5669) joined the fleet of 28-01-1675 at the Cape. According to Valentijn the Ceylon-fleet departed on 07-01-1675.
Captured from the English.

Second return fleet (5670-5673) under command of Ludder Brummer aboard the AZIË (5671) and Jakob Valk, master of the WAPEN VAN ZIERIKZEE (5673). At the Cape the Ceylon-fleet of 12-01-1675 joined this fleet.
Aboard the AZlË was Ludder Brummer, commandeur of the return fleet.
The DEN URIEL sailed from Ceylon and waited in Sunda Strait for the fleet of 28-01-1675.
Jakob Valk was vice-commandeur of the return fleet.
The ship sailed from the Cape together with the return fleet of 18-11-1674.
Date of arrival in the. Republic unknown; on 01-12-1675 the MUIDERBERG started its second voyage to the Indies (see 1308),

First return fleet (5676-5686) under command of Nikolaas Verburg aboard the TERNATE (5686). According to Valentijn the fleet departed on 17-11-1675. At the Cape the Ceylon-fleet of 02-01-1676 joined this fleet.
According to Daghreg. 1675 49 men on board had been privately recruited by the master of the ship, and 16 men by the Company. Acc. to K.A. 1198 the ship arrived on 11-07-1676 at Texel.
Acc. to K.A. 1198 the ship arrived at Texel on 11-07-1676.
Acc. to K.A. 1198 the ship arrived at Texel on 11-07-1676.
Acc. to K.A. 1198 the ship arrived at Texel on 11-07-1676.
Aboard the TERNATE was Nikolaas Verburg, commandeur of the return fleet. Acc. to K.A. 1198 the ship arrived at Texel on 11-07-1676.
The fleet (5687-5688) from Ceylon joined the fleet of 21-11-1675 at the Cape. According to Daghregister 1676 the BEEMSTER departed on 17-11-1675 from Ceylon, and arrived on 13-03-1676 at the Cape.
Acc. To Daghregister 1676 the ship departed on 17-11-1675 from Ceylon and arrived on 13-03-1676 at the Cape.
Second return fleet (5689-5691) under command of Klaas Voogd, master of the CEYLON (5690). The crew of the ALEXANDER included 72 seafarers.
Klaas Voogd was commandeur of the return fleet.
Acc. to Daghregister 1676: cargo 163,760. Amongst the crew were 81 seafarers.

First return fleet (5692-5700) under command of Gijsbert David Strandwijk aboard the BURCHT VAN LEIDEN (5696), Jan Bartelsz. Tand aboard the PRINS WILLEM HENDRIK (5700), and Laurens Martensz. Suiker aboard the DELFSHAVEN (5693). According to Valentijn the fleet departed on 21-11-1676 from Batavia.
Aboard the DELFSHAVEN was Laurens Martensz. Suiker, schout-by-nacht of the return fleet.
Aboard the BURCHT VAN LEIDEN was Gijsbert David Strandwijk, commandeur of the return fleet.
Aboard the PRINS WILLEM HENDRIK was Jan Bartelsz. Tand, vice-commandeur of the return fleet.
The fleet (5701-5702) from Ceylon joined perhaps the return fleet of 12-02-1677 at the Cape. Acc. to K.A. 1204 the Ceylon-fleet arrived at the Cape on 31-03-1677.

Willem Hagedoorn was commandeur of the second return fleet (5703-5706); it joined perhaps the fleet of 26-01-1677 from Ceylon at the Cape. According to Hudde 20 the WAPEN VAN ALKMAAR arrived on 04-11-1677 in patria.
According to Hudde 20 the GELE BEER arrived on 04-11-1677 in patria.

First return fleet (5707-5712) under command of Konstantijn Raust aboard the AZlË, Hendrik van Rede aboard the KORTGENE (5708) and Jan van Oosterwijk aboard the VRIJE ZEE (5711). The fleet revictuated at Pernambuco (Brazil).
Aboard the KORTGENE was Hendrik van Rede, vice-commandeur of the return fleet.
Aboard the VRIJE ZEE was Jan van Oosterwijk, schout-by-nacht of the return fleet.
The fleet (5713-5714) from Ceylon did not call at the Cape, but called at Fernando Noronha (27-04 till 02-06-1678).
Second return fleet (5715-5717) under command of Jan Hendriksz. Boon, master of the POULERON (5717). Aboard the BLOEMENDAAL there were probably also seafarers privately recruited by the master.
Aboard the KRIJGSMAN there were probably also seafarers privately recruited by the master.
Jan Hendriksz. Boon was commandeur of the return fleet.
Acc. to Valentijn: cargo 4,157.

First return fleet (5721-5729) under command of Jakob van der Waayen aboard the AFRIKA, Bartholomeus Nouters aboard the HENDRIK MAURTTS (5724), and Johannes Brakel aboard the HUIS TE ZILVERSTEIN (5729). Acc. to K.A. 3992 the first seven ships departed on 15-03-1679, and Acc. to Coolhaas IV on 13-03-1679.
Acc. to Hudde 20 132 seafarers and 40 soldiers on board.
Aboard the HENDRIK MAURITS was Bartholomeus Nouters, vice-commandeur of the return fleet.
36 Seafarers had been privately recruited by the master of the ship.
Sailed ahead of the fleet and joined it at the Cape.
Joined the return fleet during the voyage; according to Hudde 20, 135 seafarers on board. Aboard the HUIS TE ZILVERSTEIN was Johannes Brakel, schout-bij-nacht of the return fleet.
Sailed alone.
Sailed alone. According to K.A.1231, fol. 1618: cargo 54,065.

First return fleet (5732-5737) under command of Sybrand Abbema aboard the LAND VAN SCHOUWEN (5736), Andries Bogaard aboard the EUROPA (5734), and Dirk Timonsz. de Jonge aboard the SCHIELAND (5735). At the Cape the fleet of 09-01-1680 from Ceylon joined this fleet. In addition to the crew, 36 sick seafarers were aboard the fleet. The 60 seafarers aboard the SINT ANDRIES had been privately recruited by the master. According to Hudde 20 departure from Batavia on 11-12-1679.
The 18 impotemen were soldiers.
The 19 impotemen were soldiers. Aboard the EUROPA was Andries Bogaard, vice-commandeur of the return fleet.
The 18 impotenten were soldiers.
The 20 impotenten were soldiers. Aboard the LAND VAN SCHOUWEN was Sybrand Abbema, commandeur of the return fleet.
The 20 impotenten were soldiers.
The fleet (5738-5739) from Ceylon joined the return fleet of 24-11-1679 at the Cape.
Second return fleet (5740-5741) under command of Volkerus van Goens aboard the HUIS TE MERWEDE. The Cape was passed by on 23-05-1680.

First return fleet (5742-5745) under command of Rijklof van Goens Junior aboard the BURCHT VAN LEIDEN (5744) and Jakob Geus aboard the CHINA (5743). They were ordered to wait at the Cape until 30-03-1681 for the second return fleet (see below); only the HUIS TE ZILVERSTEIN (5748) succeeded in joining the fleet in time.
Aboard the CHINA was Jakob Geus, vice-commandeur of the return fleet.
Aboard the BURCHT VAN LEIDEN was Rijklof van Goens Junior, commandeur of the return fleet.

Master: Mol, Kornelis de Keizer or Kornelis

Particulars: Second return fleet (5746-5748) under command of Huibert Barendsz. Gruit aboard the EILAND MAURITIUS (5747). The 15 passengers aboard the BLAUWE HULK included 11 imprisoned criminals.
The 12 passengers included 8 imprisoned criminals. Aboard the EILAND MAURITIUS was Huibert Barendsz. Gruit, commondear of the return fleet.
The 12 passengers included 11 imprisoned criminals. The HUIS TE ZILVERSTEIN joined the return fleet of 29-11-1680 at the Cape.
Third return fleet (5751-5752). The master died at the Cape.
Acc. to Daghregister 1680/1: cargo of 605,705.
Fourth return fleet (5753-5754). Acc. to Valentyn the fleet departed on 21-03-1681 from Batavia.
Jan Wittebol is also mentioned as master.

First return fleet (5755-5757) under command of Rijklof van Goens Senior aboard the LAND VAN SCHOUWEN(5757). At the Cape the second return fleet of 20-12-1681, the ships of 20-01-1682 from Ceylon, and the BURCHT VAN LEIDEN (5763) joined this fleet; Leendert Maas, master of the LAND VAN SCHOUWEN, became vice-commandeur and embarked on the HOLLANDSE TUIN (5758).
Aboard the LAND VAN SCHOUWEN was Rijklof van Goens, admiraal of the return fleet. At the Cape Leendert Maas disembarked; he became vice-commandeur aboard the HOLLANDSE TUIN.

The second return fleet (5758-5759) was severely damaged by a storm off Cape Agulhas. It joined the return fleet of 26-11-1681 at the Cape. At the Cape vice-commandeur Leendert Maas embarked on the HOLLANDSE TUIN (See also 5757).
Via Malabar.
The ship from Ceylon (5760-5762) joined the return fleet of 26-11-1681 at the Cape. Acc. To Daghregister 1682 the WESTERAMSTEL arrived on 15-04-1682 at the Cape.
Departed from the Cape with the return fleet of 26-11-1681. According to K.A. 1243. fol. 808 the ship left the Cape on 28-08-1682 with a cargo of 425,315.
According to Hudde 20 the crew of the CHINA consisted of 110 seafarers and 37 soldiers. Acc. to Valentyn the ships from Ceylon (5764-5766) departed on 30-01-1683.
According to Coolhaas IV the ship departed on 06-06-1683 from the Cape. Acc. to Hudde 20 the crew consisted of 86 seafarers and 18 soldiers.

Return fleet (5767-5774) under command of Hendrik van Oudshoorn aboard the TIDORE (5774). The STRIJEN waited for the fleet of 27-02-1683 in Sunda Strait. Originally the WESTBROEK (5779) and the HUIS TE SPUK (5777) also belonged to this fleet, but they had to return to Batavia because of leakage.
The AZIË was wrecked on 17° N.

Master: Kraaienstein, Michiel van der Buis or Gijsbert
Particulars: According to Hudde 20: 11 soldiers on board. Severely damaged by storms the EUROPA had to call at Mauritius (08-05 till 29-09-1683) and for more than five months at the Cape, where it was repaired. It waited for the return fleet of 26-12-1683.
Aboard the TIDORE was Hendrik van Oudshoorn, commandeur of the return fleet. On 27-09-1683 the ship was wrecked at Ameland.
Departed from the Cape with the return fleet of 27-02-1683. Date of arrival in the Republic unknown.

First return fleet (5776-5779) under command of Steven Schorer aboard the ADRICHEM. Via Algoa Bay(17till ± 20-03) and Saldanha Bay (24-03 till 01-04-1684). At the Cape the EUROPA of the return fleet of 27-02-1683, the PURMER (5789), the EMMENES (5790), and the ships of 16-01-1684 from Ceylon joined this fleet.

The master was also called Jan van Dorre. Original departure of the HUIS TE SPIJK and the WESTBROEK (5779) on 25-02-1683. Both ships had to return to Batavia because of leakage, 30-04-1683 (see also 5767).
See 5767 and 5777.
The ships (5780-5781) from Ceylon joined the return fleet of 26-12-1683 at the Cape. Acc. to K.A. 1271 the crew consisted of 134 men.

Chamber for which cargo is destined: Amsterdam Zeeland Rotterdam Delft Hoorn Enkhuizen

Particulars: Second return fleet (5782-5788) under command of Jorephas Vos aboard the RIDDERSCHAP VAN HOLLAND (5787). According to Valentijn the fleet departed on 16-02-1684. Acc. to K.A. 1271 the fleet had a crew of 1022 men, among whom 133 soldiers and 53 impotenten. During a heavy storm in the Indian Ocean the AFRIKA was wrecked, 23-04-1684.
Acc. to Coolhaas IV the ship had a cargo of 476,419. Via Anjouan, one of the Comoro Islands (14-05-1684).
After a heavy storm to the Mayotte Islands to be repaired; in 1685 laid up in patria.
Via Anjouan one of the Comoro Islands (14-05-1684); in 1685 laid up in patria.
Via Anjouan, one of the Comoro Islands (14-05-1684); in 1685 laid up in patria.
Acc. to Coolhaas IV cargo of 575,813. Via Anjouan, one of the Comoro Islands (14-05-1684). Aboard the RIDDERSCHAP VAN HOLLAND was Jorephas Vos, commandeur of the return fleet.
Acc. to Coolhaas IV cargo of 457,535.
Via Ceylon. Acc. to K.A.191, 625-7: cargo of 466,497.
Departed from the Cape with the return fleet of 26-12-1683. Date of arrival in the Republic unknown.

First return fleet (5792-5796) under command of Matthias Luchtenburg aboard the PRINSELAND (5795). At the Cape the ships from Ceylon (5798-5800) and the ROMEIN (5797) from Bengal joined the fleet. According to K.A. 1283 and 1284 the PRINSES MARIA (5794) was the admiraal's ship and the VRIJHEID (5796) the vice-admiraal's.
The KORTGENE was the vice-commandeur's ship.
Probably the same master as mentioned under voyage no. 1451. See also 5792.
Aboard the PRINSELAND was Matthias Luchtenburg, commandeur of the return fleet.
See also 5792.
Acc. to K.A. 1284 the ship departed on 31-12-1684 from Bengal; it joined the return fleet of 28-11-1684 at the Cape.
At the Cape the ships from Ceylon (5789-5800) under command of Salomon Lesage aboard the HUIS TE ZILVERSTEIN (5799) joined the return fleet of 28-11-1684 from Batavia.
Aboard the HUIS TE ZILVERSTEIN was Salomon Lesage, commandeur of the return fleet.
Acc. to Hudde 20 the ship departed on 10-01-1685 from Ceylon.
Second return fleet (5801-5802). At the Cape the SINT MAARTENSDIJK (5803) joined this fleet. At S. Nicolas Bay one seafarer, 6 soldiers, and 3 craftsmen left the JAMBY for the BEURS VAN AMSTERDAM.
See also 5801.
Acc. to Valentijn the ship departed on 07-02-1685 from Batavia.
Acc. to K.A. 1319 the ship arrived on 01-03-1686 at the Cape. The JAVA joined the return fleet of 04-12-1685 at the Cape.

First return fleet (5806-5811) under command of Willem Karel Hartsink aboard the BANTAM. At the Cape the JAVA (5805), the GROTE VISSERIJ (5813), and the ships from Ceylon (5814-5816) joined this fleet.
Acc. to Hudde 20 the ship arrived on 29-07-1686 at Texel.
Acc. to Valentijn the ship departed on 06-12-1685 from Bengal. On 16-02-1686 it was wrecked at Terra de Natal.
The ship joined the return fleet of 04-12-1685 at the Cape.
The ships from Ceylon (5814-5816) joined the return fleet of 04-12-1685 at the Cape.
Second return fleet (5818-5819). Acc. to Valentijn the fleet departed on 24-02-1686 from Batavia. Acc. to K.A. 1307 the fleet departed on 17-06-1686 from the Cape.

The 109 men aboard the WAPEN VAN ALKMAAR included 3 craftsmen and 4 impotenten. According to Valentijn the ships from Coromandel (5820-5821) departed on 13-10-1686. They joined the return fleet of 13-12-1686 at the Cape.

First return fleet (5822-5827) under command of Daniel Braams aboard the CASTRICUM (5823). According to Valentijn the fleet departed on 30-11-1686 from Batavia. At the Cape the ships from Masulipatnam (5820-5821) and from Ceylon (5829-5832) and the DEN HELDER (5828) from Bengal joined this fleet.
Aboard the CASTRICUM was Daniel Braams, commandeur of the return fleet.
Acc. to Valentijn the ship departed on 31-12-1686 from Bengal. It joined the return fleet of 13-12-1686 at the Cape.
The ships from Ceylon (5829-5832) joined the return fleet of 13-12-1686 at the Cape.

Master: Hoorn, Meindert van Enkhuizen or Cornelis van

Particulars: Second return fleet (5833-5834).
First return fleet (5835-5839) under command of Jakob Kouper aboard the LANDS WELVAREN (5839). At the Cape the EENHOORN (5840) and the ships from Ceylon (5841-5845) joined the fleet.

Because of a storm the GOUDESTEIN had to return to Batavia, 31-12-1687; second departure from Batavia: 11-01-1688. The second amount indicated under "Inv. value" was destined for the other five Chambers of the Company.
Aboard the LANDS WELVAREN was Jakob Kouper, commandeur of the return fleet.
Acc. to Valentijn the ship departed on 10-12-1687.
According to Valentijn the fleet from Ceylon (5841-5845) departed on 22-01-1688, Acc. To K.A. 4002 on 23-01-1688. It joined the return fleet of 01-12-1687 at the Cape.
The ship joined the second return fleet of 16-03-1688 at the Cape.
According to Valentijn the second return fleet (5847-5848) departed on 28-02-1688 from Batavia. At the Cape the NIEUWLAND (5846) joined this fleet.

First return fleet (5849-5854) under command of Robertus Padbrugge aboard the OOSTERLAND (5851) and Guelter Zeeman. Acc. to Valentijn the fleet departed on 31-12-1688 from Batavia. At the Cape the ships from Ceylon (5855-5857) joined this fleet.
Aboard the OOSTERLAND was Robertus Padbrugge, commandeur of the return fleet.
The first fleet from Ceylon (5855-5857) joined the return fleet of 25-12-1688 at the Cape.
The second fleet from Ceylon (5858-5860) joined the second return fleet of 02-03-1689 at the Cape.
Second return fleet (5861-5862). Acc. to Valentijn the fleet departed on 07-03-1689 from Batavia. At the Cape the fleet of 27-02-1689 from Ceylon joined this fleet.
In 1690 burned down at Amsterdam.
Acc. to K.A. 4004 the ship departed on 06-04- 1689 from Batavia.

First return fleet (5865-5872) under command of Johan Parve aboard the NEDERLAND (5866) and Abraham Post aboard the LAND VAN SCHOUWEN (5870). At the Cape the first fleet of 07-02-1690 (except the CHINA, 5874) and the second of 12-03-1690 from Ceylon joined the fleet. The KAPELLE was wrecked near the Shetland Islands.
Aboard the NEDERLAND was Johan Parve, commandeur of the return fleet.
The PIJLSWAART was wrecked near the Shetland Islands.
Sold after arrival at Veere.
Aboard the LAND VAN SCHOUWEN was Abraham Post, vice-commandeur of the return fleet. The ship went astray from the fleet at 62°N. and was wrecked near the Shetland Islands.
The first ships from Ceylon (5873-5875) joined the first return fleet of 29-12-1689 at the Cape. The WAPEN VAN ALKMAAR was wrecked near the Shetland Islands.
Badly damaged by storm the CHINA had to wait at Mauritius for materials from the Cape. It left the island on 08-11-1690.
The second fleet from Ceylon (5876-5878) joined the first return fleet of 29-12-1689 at the Cape.
Second return fleet (5879-5882). It left the Cape under command of Paulus Huntum, master aboard the PRINSELAND (5882).
At the Cape Paulus Huntum became commandeur of the return fleet.
Probably the first ship built in the Indies and used for a homeward-bound voyage. Date of arrival in the Republic unknown.
The ships from Bengal (5885-5886) sailed from the Cape together with the CHINA (5874), the fleet of 02-03-1691 from Ceylon, the ALIDA (5892), and the ENGEL MICHAËL (5893).
Fleet from Ceylon (5887-5889). See also 5885.
Second return fleet (5890-5891).

First return fleet (5894-5899) under command of Willem Kemp, master of the WATERLAND (5899). At the Cape the fleet of 28-02-1692 from Ceylon and the MOERKAPEL (5905) joined this fleet. The EENHOORN sailed via Saldanha Bay (21 till 27-05-1692). According to K.A. 4007 its crew consisted of 146 men.
Acc. to K.A . 4007 the crew consisted of 184 men. Via Saldanha Bay (01 till 27-05-1692).
Acc. to K.A. 4007 the crew consisted of 146 men. Via Saldanha Bay (21 till 27-05-1692).
Acc. toK.A. 4007 the crew consisted of 125 men. Via Saldanha Bay (01 till 27-05-1692).
Acc. to K.A. 4390a the master was Pieter Pietersz. The ship probably did not call at the Cape.

Willem Kemp was commandeur of the return fleet. Acc. to K.A. 4007 the crew consisted of 184 men. The WATERLAND sailed via Saldanha Bay (01 till 21-05-1692). On 12-09-1692 the ship was attacked by the French and sunk with all hands at 45°N.

The ship from Ceylon (5900-5903) joined the return fleet of 30-01-1692 at the Cape. The GOEDE HOOP was wrecked at the Cape, 05-06-1692; from the cargo 562,488 was saved and carried to patria aboard the EMMENES (5911).
Acc. to K.A. 4390a the ship arrived on 10-12-1692 at Veere.
On 10-06-1692 the HOGERGEEST was wrecked at the Cape.
Joined the return fleet of 30-01-1692 at the Cape.

First return fleet (5906-5910) under command of Jan van den Berg; he died before arrival at the Cape. Abraham Zeeman, master of the NEDERLAND (5907), succeeded him. At the Cape the HANDBOOG (5912) joined the fleet. Acc. to K.A. 4007 the crew of the DRECHTERLAND consisted of 125 men.
Acc. to K.A. 4007 the crew consisted of 150 men. Abraham Jakobsz. Zeeman succeeded Jan van den Berg as commandeur of the return fleet (see 5906).
Acc. to K.A. 4007 the crew consisted of 120 men. At least one passenger was on board.
Acc. to K.A. 4007 the crew consisted of 120 men.
Acc. to K.A. 4007 the crew consisted of 128 men. Acc. to K.A. 4390a the name of the master was Jakob Klaasz. Mouthaan.
The EMMENES originally was only bound for the Cape, but it had to carry the cargo saved from the GOEDE HOOP (5900) to patria. At the Cape the ship joined the second return fleet of 08-02-1693.
The ship joined the first return fleet of 11-12-1692 at the Cape.

Second return fleet (5913-5916); at the Cape the fleet of 28-02-1693 from Ceylon, the EMMENES (5911), and the SCHIEBROEK (5921) joined this fleet. Herman Voet, master of the BERKEL, was in command of the combined fleet. Ace to K.A. 4009 the BERKEL's crew consisted of 97 men.
Acc. to K.A. 4009 the crew consisted of 92 men.
Acc. to K.A. 4009 the crew consisted of 120 men.
Acc. to K.A. 4009 the crew consisted of 133 men.
The ships from Ceylon (5917-5920) joined the return fleet of 08-02-1693 at the Cape.
Acc. to K.A. 4009 the crew consisted of 140 men.
Acc. to K.A. 4009 the crew consisted of 90 men.
Acc. to K.A. 4009 the ship departed on 16-03-1693 from Batavia and had a crew of 45 men. It joined the return fleet of 08-02-1693 at the Cape. In 1694 sold in patria.

First return fleet (5922-5927). At the Cape the ships of 23-01-1694 joined this fleet. The combined fleet was under command of Hendrik Prank and Adriaan van Laren. The 10 'passengers' aboard the BANTAM were French prisoners.
The 8 'passengers' were French prisoners. Acc. to K.A. 4009 the crew consisted of 138 men.
Acc. to K.A. 4009 the crew consisted of 110 men. The 'passengers' were French prisoners.
Acc. to K.A. 4009 the crew consisted of 151 men . The 'passengers' were French prisoners.
Acc. to K.A. 4009 the crew consisted of 125 men. The 'passengers' were French prisoners.
Acc. to K.A. 4009 the crew consisted of 101 men. The 'passengers' were French prisoners.
The ships from Ceylon (5928-5929) joined the return fleet of 07-12-1693 at the Cape.
Second return fleet (5930-5933) under command of Jan Speelman, master of the NIGTEVECHT (5932).
Jan Speelman was commandeur of the return fleet.

First return fleet (5934-5941) under command of Reinierde Vos aboard the KONING WILLIAM (5941). At the Cape the BERKEL (5942), the fleet of 26-01-1695 from Ceylon, and the second return fleet of 04-02-1695 joined this fleet. Acc. to K.A. 4012 the crew of the KRAB consisted of 104 men. The 11 passengers included 8 French prisoners.
Acc. to K.A. 4012 the crew consisted of 150 men. The 10 'passengers' were French prisoners.
Acc. to K.A. 4012 the crew consisted of 140 men. Amongst the passengers were 10 French prisoners.
Acc. to K.A. 4012 the crew consisted of 124 men. The 9 'passengers' were French prisoners.
Acc. to K.A. 4012 the crew consisted of 148 men. Amongst the passengers were 10 French prisoners.
Acc. to K.A. 4012 the crew consisted of 129 men. The 21 passengers aboard the WADDINXVEEN included the Reverend Francois Valentijn and 10 French prisoners.
Acc. to K.A.4012 the crew consisted of 142 men. Amongst the passengers were 10 French prisoners.
Acc. to K.A. 4012 the crew consisted of 150 men. Amongst the passengers were 10 French prisoners. Aboard the KONING WILLIAM was Reinier de Vos, commandeur of the return fleet.
Acc. to K.A. 4012 the ship departed on 25-12-1694 from Batavia with a crew of 104 men.
According to K.A. 4013 R. de Vos was commandeur of the return fleet (5943-5946). The MAAS was sold in Zeeland in 1696.
Commandeur of the return fleet (5950-5960) was Jan de Wit, master of the OOSTERSTEIN (5956); schout-by-nacht was Dirk Thomasz. aboard the BELOIS. The fleet did not call at the Cape but at St. Helena.
Jan de Wit was commandeur of the return fleet.
The master was vice-commandeur of the return fleet.
During the Voyage Isaak Lambrechtsen succeeded Kornelis de Gaver as master.
According to K.A . 1475 the ROSKAM was taken by the French, successively by the English, and finally restored to the Company.

The BANTAM was wrecked off Vlissingen, 03-12-1697. Aboard the BANTAM was Hendrik Pronk, commandeur of the return fleet (5962-5973); he died during the voyage and was buried at the Cape. Schout-by-nacht Hendrik Gravia aboard the DRIEBERGEN (5964) replaced him. Hendrik van Buitenhem was vice-commandeur aboard the STAD KEULEN (5967).
At the departure from Batavia Koenraad Warnarsz. might have been the master.
Aboard the DRIEBERGEN was Hendrik Gravia, schout-bij-nacht of the return fleet.
Aboard the STAD KEULEN was Hendrik van Buitenhem, vice-commandeur of the return fleet. Full cargo list printed in Glamann, p. 23/24.
At the departure from Batavia Jan Abrahamsz. Oldenhove might not yet have been aboard, (see also 5976).
The WADDINXVEEN was wrecked at the Cape, 24-05-1697; 4 men were saved.
The OOSTERLAND was wrecked in the Table Bay, 24-05-1697.
At the departure from Ceylon Jan Abrahamsz. Oldenhove might have been the master, see also 5968.
Sailed via Persia.

Commandeur of the return fleet (5981-5988) was Klaas Bichon aboard the LANDS WELVAREN (5988); at the Cape he embarked on the ISSELT (5989). Vice-commandeur was Paulus Huntum aboard the DOMBURG (5982).
Aboard the DOMBURG was Paulus Huntum, vice-commandeur of the return fleet.
Aboard the LANDS WELVAREN was Klaas Bichon, commandeur of the return fleet; at the Cape he embarked on the ISSELT (5989).
See also 5981 and 5988.
The NOORDGOUW carried the cargoes of the WADDINXVEEN and the OOSTERLAND, both wrecked at the Cape (see 5973 and 5975).
The crew included 6 impotenten.
The crew included 6 impotenten.
Willem de Vlaming was commandeur of the return fleet (5993-5997 and 5999).
The crew included 3 impotenten.
According to K.A. 4017 the crew consisted of 48 men.
The crew included 7 impotenten.

According to K.A. 4017 the crew consisted of 120 men. Commandeur of the return fleet (6000-6008) was Daniel Henens sailing aboard the OOSTERSTEIN (6003); vice-commandeur was Albert Buis aboard the VOSMAAR (6006); schout-bij-nacht Covert van Wierden was aboard the REIGERSDAAL (6004).
Aboard the OOSTERSTEIN was Daniel Henens, commandeur of the return fleet.
Aboard the REIGERSDAAL was Govert van Wierden, schout-bij-nacht of the return fleet.
Aboard the VOSMAAR was Albert Buis, vice-commandeur of the return fleet.
Laid up at the Cape, 1700.
Laid up at the Cape, 27-02-1700.
Carried the cargo of the NIEUWLAND (6012), which had been laid up at the Cape in 1700.
Commandeur of the return fleet (6018-6025) was Wouter Valkenier aboard the KATTENDIJK (6020); vice-commandeur was Wijbrand Lycochton aboard the CONCORDIA.
Aboard the KATTENDIJK was Wouter Valkenier, commandeur of the return fleet.
At the arrival at Goeree, Meindert de Boer probably was master.
Commandeur of the return fleet from Ceylon (6028-6031) was Jan Gerritsz. van Bordeaux, master of the SPIEGEL (6029).
Jan Gerritsz. van Bordeaux was commandeur of the return fleet.
Wrecked on 29-05-1700 off Pernambuco.
Carried the cargo of the WAALSTROOM (6015), which had been laid up at the Cape in 1700.
Jakob Onkruid was commandeur of the return fleet (6037-6039).

Commandeur of the return fleet (6040-6047) was Kornelis Koleman, master of the LIEFDE (6044); Kornelis Jorisz. Oversluis, master of the DOMBURG (6041 ), was vice-commandeur, schout-bij-nacht was Abraham Oudenhoorn, master of the SCHOONDERLOO (6047).
Kornelis Jorisz. Oversluis was vice-commandeur of the return fleet.
Kornelis Koleman was commandeur of the return fleet.
Abraham Oudenhoorn was schout-bij-nacht of the return fleet.
Missing between Batavia and the Cape
Commandeur of the return fleet (6054-6056) was Alexander Simons, master of the THEEBOOM (6056).
Alexander Simons was commandeur of the return fleet.
Commandeur of the combined return fleet (6058-6075) was Harman Voet aboard the GENERALE VREDE (6066); schout-bij-nacht was Gerrit Kollaart, master of the SION (6067).
During the voyage Isaak Philipsz. succeeded Pieter Donker as master.
Aboard the GENERALE VREDE was Harman Voet, commandeur of the return fleet.
Gerrit Collaart was schout-bij-nacht of the return fleet.

Commandeur of the combined return fleet (6079-6093) was Jakob Brock, master of the SPIEGEL (6087); Jan de Wersijn, master of the OOSTERSTEIN (6085), was vice-commandeur; schout-bij-nacht was Jakob Joppe de Jong, master of the REIGERSDAAL (6086).
Jan de Wersijn was vice-commandeur of the combined return fleet.
Jakob Joppe de Jong was schout-bij-nacht of the combined return fleet.
Jakob Broek was commandeur of the combined fleet.
After this voyage the ship was sold.
Since 13-11-1703 in Norway, where a temporary embargo was laid on ship and cargo.
Since 13-11-1703 in Norway, where a temporary embargo was laid on ship and cargo.
Since 13-11-1703 in Norway, where a temporary embargo was laid on ship and cargo.

Commandeur of the combined return fleet (6097-6112) was Adolf Winkler aboard the WESTHOVEN (6104); vice-commandeur was Diedlof Kroes, master of the GENERALE VREDE (6105); schout-bjj-nacht was Kornelis Valk, master of the DONKERVLIET (6098).
Kornelis Valk was schout-bij-nacht of the return fleet.
Aboard the WESTHOVEN were Adolf Winkler, commandeur of the return fleet, and his family.
Diedlof Kroes was vice-commandeur of the return fleet.

The 22 passengers aboard the AMSTERDAM included admiraal Adriaan Valkenier with 5 servants and 13 lijfschutten (bodyguards). At the Cape this former Gouverneur-Generaal was arrested; he was accused by the future G.-G. Van Imhoff of being responsible for the notorious 'Chinese Murders' in Batavia in 1740. In August, 1742, Valkenier was transported back to Batavia (see 3241). The AMSTERDAM was wrecked off the Shetland Islands.

The NAARSTIGHEID departed from Bengal twelve days late (see 7498 and 7499). In June 1757 the ship reached Delagoa Bay in a very tumbledown conditon; on 01-07-1757 the NAARSTIGHEID was finally given up and set on fire. Its cargo was transported to the Cape by the HECTOR (see 3557), which sailed twice from the Cape to the Bay, and by the SCHOLTENBURG, which had arrived at the Cape in March 1 759 (see 3743). The SCHOLTENBURG finally carried the cargo from the Cape to patria in 1760 (see 7581).

The VROUWE ELISABETH DOROTHEA departed from Batavia with at least 91 men on board; the 2 passengers were condemned persons. The ship called at St. Helena (departure on 09-09). During the voyage 12 members of the crew died. In the night of 27/28-11-1767 the VROUWE ELISABETH DOROTHEA ran ashore between Petten and Callantsoog and was wrecked; only 6 persons were rescued, (see P. Dekker). See also the VREEBURG (4030).
The 6 passengers included 2 condemned persons.
The 11 passengers included 2 slaves. Commandeur of the return fleet was Jan van Eysden, master of the DUINENBURG (7741).
The master of the DUINENBURG, Jan van Eysden, was commandeur of the return fleet.
The 10 passengers included one condemned person.

The 6 passengers included one condemned person. The OUDERAMSTEL carried, among other things, tea, destined for the chamber Amsterdam; value: f 103,944. 3981/7747 was the first voyage of this ship, which during the outward voyage was called AZIË.

The 2 passengers were condemned persons. On 23-04-1768 the AZIË arrived at Bourbon, an island near Mauritius; it was laid up there because of irreparability. 3912/7756 was the third and last voyage of this ship, which during its first two voyages and the third outward voyage was called OUDERAMSTEL.
The 5 passengers included 2 condemned persons.
The 4 passengers were condemned persons.
The 111 persons aboard the JERUSALEM included 2 passengers. The ship was laid up at Rotterdam on 08-10-1770.
The 3 passengers included one condemned person. Commandeur of the return fleet was Dirk Wagtels, master of the BORSSELE (7766).

The master of the BORSSELE, Dirk Wagtels, was commandeur of the return fleet.

4041/7798 was the fifth voyage of this ship, which during its first three voyages was called TORENVLIET (3783/7616).
The 114 persons aboard the SCHAGEN included one passenger.

The ENKHUIZEN was wrecked between Bengal and the Cape.
The VAILLANT was wrecked between Bengal and the Cape.
The master of the KRONENBURG, Frederik Kelger, was commandeur of the return fleet.

One of the 2 passengers was a condemned person. At the Cape the DAMZICHT was declared unseaworthy; its cargo was transported to Amsterdam by the ZON (see 7841). The DAMZICHT was laid up at the Cape on 10-02-1772.
The men aboard the RENSWOUDE included one passenger.
The 28 persons who went ashore at the Cape, included Steven Booms; he had to disembark because of illness. Koenraad Louwe succeeded him as master of the DUIVENBRUG.
The ZON transported the cargo of the DAMZICHT, taken off the service at the Cape, April 1771 (see 7835); invoice value: f 189,914, destined for the chamber Amsterdam.
The RIJNSBURG was bound for the Republic via China and Bengal; sailing to China, however, it was wrecked in 1772. See also the HERSTELDER (7877).
The 14 passengers included one condemned person and 4 slaves.

The 7 passengers included 3 slaves (among whom a woman and her child). Admiraal of the return fleet was Johan Vos, sailing aboard  the JONGE THOMAS  (7854);  Pieter  Kornelisz. Hasselaar, aboard the AZIË (7847), was commandeur.

The 10 passengers included 3 slaves. Aboard the AZIË was Pieter Kornelisz. Hasselaar, commandeur of the return fleet. 4032/7847 was the second voyage of this ship, which during its first outward voyage (3981) was called AZIË, and during the first return voyage (7747) and the second outward voyage (4032) OUDERAMSTEL; after June, 1769, the ship was renamed AZIË.
The 6 passengers included one condemned person.

The 7 passengers included 2 condemned persons. Serious damage forced the WELGELEGEN to call at Rio Delagoa. The ship was laid up at Hoorn on 09-10-1773.

The 11 passengers included  3 condemned persons. Commandeur of the return fleet was Arend van der Deuren, master of the NOORD-BEVELAND (7874).
The 6 passengers included one female slave.
The 7 passengers included 2 condemned persons.
The master of the NOORD-BEVELAND, Arend van der Deuren, was commandeur of the return fleet. After its return the NOORD-BEVELAND served as a hospital-ship; on 09-10-1773 it was laid up.
The HERSTELDER, bought in China, replaced the RIJNSBURG, which had been wrecked during a voyage from Batavia to China in 1771/2 (see 7842).
The DUINENBURG was wrecked between the Cape and patria.
One of the 2 passengers was a condemned person.
The VROUWE MARGARETHA MARIA was bound for patria via Bengal, but on its way to Bengal it was wrecked in 1773.
Commandeur of the return fleet was Leendert van Koopstad, master of the 'T LOO (7898).

4148/7896 was the third voyage of this ship, which during its first outward voyage (3981) was called AZlË, and during the first return voyage (7747) and the second outward voyage (4032) OUDERAMSTEL; subsequently it was renamed AZIË again (see 7847, etc.).
The 4 passengers included one condemned person.
The master of the 'T LOO, Leendert van Koopstad, was commandeur of the return fleet.

According to K.A. 4261 Gerard Oosthuis was master of the PRINSES VAN ORANJE.

Between 14 and 16-05-1777 the DUIVENBRUG was wrecked off the Canary Islands.
On 11-10-1777 the WESTERVELD was laid up.

On 31-08-1777 the OVERHOUT ran ashore near Egmond aan Zee and was wrecked.
After the arrival of the ship at Texel its name was altered into COMPAGNIES WELVAREN (see the second voyage: 4345/-).
The master of the VROUWE ANTHOINETTA KOENRARDINA, Gerrit Harmeyer, was commandeur of the return fleet.
4 of the 5 passengers were condemned persons. According to K.A. 4390a Cristiaan Frederik Winterheim was master of the VRIJHEID.
The 7 passengers included one female slave.

The VENUS ran ashore at Rio Delagoa; not earlier than 27-11-1779 it was able to continue the return voyage via the Cape to Texel. After the return in patria the VENUS was sold to Prussia, and its name was altered into OOSTEREEM, and subsequently the ship was hired by the VOC (see 4406/-).
The EENDRACHT was wrecked between Batavia and the Cape.
According to K.A. 4390a Herman Volkers was master of the PATRIOT.
The master of the BEHEMOTH, Hendrik Nieuwboer, was commandeur of the return fleet.
